    <fr:title text="Lebesgue integral">Lebesgue integral</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
    <fr:date>
      <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
      <fr:month>5</fr:month>
      <fr:day>26</fr:day>
    </fr:date>
    <fr:authors />
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>The Lebesgue integral is a generalization of the Riemann integral that allows for the integration of a broader class of functions. It is defined for <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001L.xml" addr="FA-001L" title="Measurable function">measurable functions</fr:link> on a measure space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X, \mathcal {A}, \mu )]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>The construction of the Lebesgue integral proceeds in several steps:</fr:p>
    <fr:ol><fr:li>First, define the integral for non-negative <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001O.xml" addr="FA-001O" title="Simple function">simple functions</fr:link> (finite linear combinations of indicator functions of measurable sets).</fr:li>
<fr:li>Then, extend this definition to non-negative measurable functions using monotone approximation by simple functions.</fr:li>
<fr:li>Finally, define the integral for general measurable functions by separately integrating their positive and negative parts.</fr:li></fr:ol>
    <fr:p>The Lebesgue integral has many advantages over the Riemann integral:</fr:p>
    <fr:ul><fr:li>It allows for the integration of a larger class of functions</fr:li>
<fr:li>It has better convergence properties, exemplified by the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001F.xml" addr="FA-001F" title="Monotone Convergence Theorem">Monotone Convergence Theorem</fr:link> and <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001E.xml" addr="FA-001E" title="Lebesgue's Dominated Convergence Theorem">Lebesgue's Dominated Convergence Theorem</fr:link></fr:li>
<fr:li>It provides a more natural setting for limiting operations and for the study of function spaces like <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p]]></fr:tex> spaces</fr:li></fr:ul>
  </fr:mainmatter>
